# Research session-capture coverage across the fleet

READ-ONLY reconnaissance for the observational-memory write loop
(`.brain/projects/observational-memory/observational-memory-brief.svx`). You are
on flagg in `~/Code/joelhooks/joelclaw`. Ground truth only — receipts for
every claim (the exact command + trimmed output). No mutations anywhere: no
writes to Typesense, no config changes, no commits.

## Questions to answer, per agent surface (pi / claude / codex) × machine (flagg / blaine / panda)

1. **Where do session transcripts land?** Exact paths, formats (jsonl?),
   naming. Use the `joelclaw` CLI (`joelclaw sessions --help`), the
   session-search machinery, and direct filesystem inspection. For blaine and
   panda use read-only ssh (`ssh joel@blaine '<cmd>'`, panda by tailnet IP if
   MagicDNS fails — see `~/.brain/resources/operator-network-context.svx`).
2. **What reaches Typesense?** Collections, document counts, freshness
   (newest doc timestamp per source×machine), what fields are indexed.
3. **Change ledger status**: where the Pi runtime v1 ledger
   (session→commit attribution) actually runs today, and what it covers.
4. **Volumes**: sessions/day and rough tokens/day per surface×machine over
   the last 7 days — this sizes observer triggers and budgets.
5. **Gaps, named**: any surface×machine combination that is NOT captured,
   stale, or unindexed. A gap is a finding, not a failure.

## Output

Write `.brain/resources/session-capture-coverage-2026-07.svx` in THIS repo
(svx with small frontmatter — never .md, that is the law): a coverage matrix
(surface × machine → path, capture mechanism, indexed?, freshness, volume),
receipts folded per cell, and a short "what this means for observer design"
closing section. Print a DONE summary with the matrix in compact text form
and your top 3 findings. Do not commit.
